Wash and dry all produce. Preheat #oven to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot
of salted water to a boil. Cut @heirloom grape tomatoes{8%oz} into quarters.
Pick leaves from @parsley{¼%oz}; discard stems. Roughly chop leaves. Cut
@fresh mozzarella{8%oz} into ½-inch cubes. Mince or grate @garlic{4%clove}.

Once water is boiling, add @orzo pasta{12%oz} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Drain.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a large #pan over medium-high heat.
Pat @sirloin steak{24%oz} dry with a paper towel, then season all over with
@herbs de Provence{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Add to pan and cook until
browned, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #baking sheet{}. Roast in
oven to desired doneness, ~{7-10%minutes}.

Heat another drizzle of olive oil in same pan over medium heat. Add
garlic and cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Add tomatoes and cook
until slightly softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add orzo, mozzarella, @balsamic vinegar{2%tablespoon}, a drizzle of olive
oil, and ¾ of the parsley to pan. Stir to combine. Season with salt and
pepper.

Thinly slice steak against the grain. Divide pasta salad between plates and
top with steak. Garnish with remaining parsley and serve.

> Caprese salad—that's mozzarella, tomato, and balsamic—is addictive as an
> appetizer. But in this recipe perfect for both lunch and dinner, we're
> turning it into a main event. Seared sirloin steak adds some meaty heft to
> the meal, while orzo pasta fills it out and soaks up all the flavorful
> juices. Throw in some garlic and a drizzle of olive oil for flavor and
> you'll realize at first bite, that's amore.